Lego Sets: An Analysis Project

The following project is a descriptive analysis on multiple Lego sets between 2018 and 2020. The goal of the project is to extract meaningful data and represent it in a comprehensible graphical format that could serve to improve decision making relative to the Lego market.

Libraries

library (tidyverse) 
library (ggplot2) 
library (dplyr)
library (gridExtra)

Data loading

setwd("C:/Users/andre/OneDrive/Escritorio/Lego Project")
lego_data <- read.csv("lego_population_cof.csv")

2. Data cleaning

In this section, various changes into the data will take place, such as removing unnecessary columns, NA values, changing values to a more useful format and creating new variables.

This changes will help us get a dataset of higher quality, clean enough to perfom better analysis.

2.1. Taking down unnecessary columns.

lego_data <- lego_data %>%
  dplyr::select(-Item_Number, -Amazon_Price, -Pages, -Price)

2.2. Remove NA values from âSet_Nameâ

lego_data <- lego_data %>%
  drop_na(Set_Name)

2.3. Divide weights by KG and LB in different variables.

lego_data <- lego_data %>%
  mutate(
    Weight_kg = str_extract(Weight, "\\d+\\.\\d+(?=Kg)"),  
    Weight_lb = str_extract(Weight, "(?<=\\().*?(?=\\slb)")  
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Weight_kg = as.numeric(Weight_kg),
    Weight_lb = as.numeric(Weight_lb)
  )%>%
  select(-Weight)

2.4.Removing NA values from ages.

lego_data <- lego_data %>%
  filter(Ages != "Ages_NA")

2.5. New variable âLowerAgeâ, taking the lowest values from âAgesâ.

lego_data <- lego_data %>%
  mutate(LowerAge = as.numeric(str_extract(Ages, "\\d+")))

2.6. New age groups classification: Kids, Teens and Adults.

lego_data <- lego_data %>%
  mutate(
    LegoKids = ifelse(LowerAge >= 1 & LowerAge <= 10, 1, 0),
    LegoTeens = ifelse(LowerAge >= 11 & LowerAge <= 17, 1, 0),
    LegoAdults = ifelse(LowerAge >= 18, 1, 0)
  )

3. Data visualization

With a clean dataset, our analysis is set to begin.

3.1. Lego sets per year and size.

Total number of Lego sets remained almost equal between 2018 and 2019, with a small increase in the proportion of Lego sets of large size. In 2020 not only did the total number of Lego sets increase, both large and small sizes increased, particularly the latter.

sets_per_year_size <- lego_data %>%
  group_by(Year, Size) %>%
  summarize(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  arrange(Year, desc(count))


sets_per_year_size <- sets_per_year_size %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  mutate(Size = fct_reorder(Size, count, .desc = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()


ggplot(sets_per_year_size, aes(x = Year, y = count, fill = Size)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack") +
  labs(title = "Number of Lego Sets per Year and Size",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of Sets",
       fill = "Size") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(alpha = 0.5,
                       option = "plasma") +  
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),  
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()  
  )

3.2. Lego sets per availability.

Most of the Lego sets were sold on retail stores, with the highest numbers in 2020. However, Lego exclusive did see a constant increase during the three years.

3.4. Lego sets by year and packaging.

Just like in the first graph representing the amount of Lego sets and their size, the box packaging type saw and increase in 2020 in comparison to the previous years. In that same year, other types of packaging like tag, plastic canister and box with backing card appeared as packaging alternatives. Interestingly, the use of polybag on Lego sets decreased each year.

3.5. Histogram functions for unique pieces, pieces, weight (kg) and minifigures.

These histograms aimed to have a closer inspection in behavioral changes along different variables concerning the Lego sets. While all variables are skewed positively, these variables behaved similar through every year.

As noticed from previous figures, total Lego sets increased during 2020. How did that increase affect the Lego sets? A proportional increase in the distribution of unique pieces, pieces and minifigures during that year can be seen in the variablesâ graphs. This explains why the weight had a considerable (and proportional) increase in its count in the values around the mode.

variables_to_plot <- c("unique_pieces", "Pieces", "Weight_kg", "Minifigures")

variable_titles <- c(
  unique_pieces = "Unique Pieces",
  Pieces = "Pieces",
  Weight_kg = "Weight (kg)",
  Minifigures = "Minifigures"
)

plots <- list()

for (var in variables_to_plot) {
  plots[[var]] <- ggplot(lego_data %>% filter(!is.na(get(var)), !is.na(Year)), aes_string(x = var)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(fill = factor(Year)), alpha = 0.7, bins = 30, position = "identity") +
    labs(
      title = paste("Histogram of", variable_titles[[var]], "by Year"),
      x = variable_titles[[var]],
      y = "Count",
      fill = "Year"
    ) +
    scale_fill_viridis_d(alpha = 0.7) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
    ) +
    facet_wrap(~ Year, ncol = 1, scales = "free_y")  
}

for (var in variables_to_plot) {
  print(plots[[var]])
}

3.6. Lego sets correlation between pieces and weight.

Pieces and weight of Lego sets correlate positively, but the r-squared value of 0.639 shows a somewhat poor correlation.

Note: Both axes are set in logarithmic scales.

model1 <- lm(log10(Weight_kg) ~ log10(Pieces), data = lego_data)
r2_1 <- summary(model1)$r.squared
print(paste("R^2 for Pieces vs Weight:", r2_1))
## [1] "R^2 for Pieces vs Weight: 0.638980997678262"
ggplot(lego_data, aes(x = Pieces, y = Weight_kg, color = Pieces)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "yellow", se = TRUE) +  
  labs(
    title = "Correlation Between Pieces and Weight of Lego Sets",
    x = "Number of Pieces",
    y = "Weight (kg)"
  ) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_color_viridis_c(alpha = 0.5) +  
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  ) +
  annotate("text", x = Inf, y = Inf, label = paste("RÂ² =", round(r2_1, 3)), 
           hjust = 1.1, vjust = 2, size = 4, color = "black")

3.7. Lego sets correlation between unique pieces and pieces.

While maybe unique pieces may seem as a replacement for pieces, the data shows that an increase in pieces also means in increment in unique pieces (evidence of that is the strong correlation showed by the r-squared value of 0.844). A possible explanation to this is that unique pieces might depend from normal pieces in order to construct the Lego set.

Another explanation could be that they could be they are independent from each other and they just gather a positive correlation without a logical explanation.

However, we could conclude from this data that, if unique pieces served as a substitute for pieces, they would not correlate positively. If it was the case, Lego sets with higher amounts of unique pieces would have a considerable decrease in the number of pieces.

Note: Both axes are set in logarithmic scales.

model2 <- lm(log10(unique_pieces) ~ log10(Pieces), data = lego_data)
r2_2 <- summary(model2)$r.squared
print(paste("R^2 for Pieces vs Unique Pieces:", r2_2))
## [1] "R^2 for Pieces vs Unique Pieces: 0.84367087682854"
ggplot(lego_data, aes(x = Pieces, y = unique_pieces)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +  
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "yellow", se = TRUE) +  
  labs(
    title = "Correlation Between Pieces and Unique Pieces of Lego Sets",
    x = "Number of Pieces",
    y = "Unique Pieces"
  ) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  scale_colour_viridis_c(alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  ) +
  annotate("text", x = Inf, y = Inf, label = paste("RÂ² =", round(r2_2, 3)), 
           hjust = 1.1, vjust = 2, size = 4, color = "black")

3.11. Lego sets per age group (LegoKids, LegoTeens and LegoAdults).

Since the amount of age groups makes it difficult to interpret the data, we created a new variable called LowerAge, where lower values of age groups were extracted (since some of the them had age intervals). The idea was to classify the Lego sets in three new different age groups:

  1. LegoKids: LowerAge =< 10
  2. LegoTeens: 10 < LowerAge >= 17
  3. LegoAdults: LowerAge >= 18

We can clearly see the LegoKids sets amount for the vast majority of the Lego sets, with a 92,7% overall.

class_counts <- lego_data %>%
  summarize(
    LegoKids = sum(LegoKids, na.rm = TRUE),
    LegoTeens = sum(LegoTeens, na.rm = TRUE),
    LegoAdults = sum(LegoAdults, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(), names_to = "Class", values_to = "Count") %>%
  mutate(Class = factor(Class, levels = c("LegoKids", "LegoTeens", "LegoAdults")))


ggplot(class_counts, aes(x = Class, y = Count, fill = Class)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Lego Sets by Age Group",
    x = "Age Group",
    y = "Number of Sets"
  ) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(alpha = 0.8) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )

3.12. Top 10 Lego themes by the amount of Lego sets.

While City is the only theme to surpass the 100 sets line, Friends and Star Wars are tied for second place.

sets_per_theme <- lego_data %>%

  summarize(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%    
  slice_head(n = 10)          


ggplot(sets_per_theme, aes(x = reorder(Theme, -count), y = count, fill = Theme)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Lego Themes by Number of Sets",
       x = "Theme",
       y = "Number of Sets") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(alpha = 0.8,
                       option = "turbo") +

    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),

    legend.position = "none"

3.13. Evolution year by year of Lego sets within the top 10 themes.

A couple of interesting cases when it comes to the year by year evolution Lego sets in the top 10 themes:

  1. Friends had an important decrease in the number of sets in 2019, just to skyrocket its numbers in 2020.
  2. Ninjago and Duplo had constant increases each year.
  3. Technic hit a plateau in the last two years.
top_themes <- lego_data %>%
  count(Theme, sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>%
  pull(Theme)


sets_per_year_theme <- lego_data %>%
  filter(Theme %in% top_themes) %>%
  group_by(Year, Theme) %>%
  summarize(count = n(), .groups = 'drop')


ggplot(sets_per_year_theme, aes(x = Year, y = count, color = Theme)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +  
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(sets_per_year_theme$Year), max(sets_per_year_theme$Year), by = 1)) +  
  labs(
    title = "Evolution of Lego Sets per Year for Top 10 Themes",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of Lego Sets",
    color = "Theme"
  ) +
  scale_colour_viridis_d(alpha = 0.5,
                         option = "turbo") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "right"
  )

3.14. Lego sets by top 10 themes and age group.

Returning to the new age groups classification, we can see most of the top 10 themes only offer sets within the LegoKids age classification. Star Wars is the theme with most representation in the LegoTeens and LegoAdults age groups in the top 10 themes.

top_themes <- lego_data %>%
  mutate(total_count = LegoKids + LegoTeens + LegoAdults) %>%
  group_by(Theme) %>%
  summarize(total_count = sum(total_count), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  arrange(desc(total_count)) %>%
  head(10) %>%
  pull(Theme)


theme_age_group_counts <- lego_data %>%
  filter(Theme %in% top_themes) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(LegoKids, LegoTeens, LegoAdults),
               names_to = "AgeGroup", values_to = "Flag") %>%
  filter(Flag == 1) %>%
  group_by(Theme, AgeGroup) %>%
  summarize(count = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>%
  mutate(
    Theme = factor(Theme, levels = top_themes),  
    AgeGroup = factor(AgeGroup, levels = c("LegoAdults", "LegoTeens", "LegoKids"))  
  )


ggplot(theme_age_group_counts, aes(x = Theme, y = count, fill = AgeGroup)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Number of Lego Sets by Theme and Age Group (Top 10 Themes)",
       x = "Theme",
       y = "Number of Sets",
       fill = "Age Group") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(alpha = 0.7) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  ) +
  coord_flip()

3.15. Distribution of pieces across the three age groups.

LegoKids age group has the narrowest distribution, which serves a logic as more pieces relate to more complex Lego sets. However, we can see many outliers in this age group.

LegoTeens and LegoAdults have wider distributions and higher boxplots than LegoKids.

age_group_data <- lego_data %>%
  select(Pieces, LegoKids, LegoTeens, LegoAdults) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(LegoKids, LegoTeens, LegoAdults), names_to = "AgeGroup", values_to = "Flag") %>%
  filter(Flag == 1)  

age_group_data$AgeGroup <- factor(age_group_data$AgeGroup, levels = c("LegoKids", "LegoTeens", "LegoAdults"))

ggplot(age_group_data, aes(x = AgeGroup, y = Pieces, fill = AgeGroup)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Pieces Across Age Groups",
    x = "Age Group",
    y = "Number of Pieces"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),

3.18. Pieces, unique pieces and minifigures count by theme (top 10 themes)

Notice the following cases:

  1. City sets amount the highest values in unique pieces and minifigures.
  2. Despite being in tied-second place, Star Wars amounts the highest value in pieces, followed by Technic (which means that theme offers a higher volume of pieces per set than most of the other themes, despite being the last theme in the top 10).
  3. BrickHeadz and Technic sets do not include minifigures, the reason being these sets` themes do not have a place for minifigures.
top_themes <- lego_data %>%
  count(Theme, sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>%
  pull(Theme)


summary_data <- lego_data %>%
  filter(Theme %in% top_themes) %>%
  group_by(Theme) %>%
  summarize(
    Pieces = sum(Pieces, na.rm = TRUE),
    Unique_Pieces = sum(unique_pieces, na.rm = TRUE),
    Minifigures = sum(Minifigures, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = 'drop'
  )


summary_long <- summary_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Pieces, Unique_Pieces, Minifigures),
               names_to = "Variable",
               values_to = "Count") %>%
  mutate(Theme = factor(Theme, levels = top_themes))  


ggplot(summary_long, aes(x = Theme, y = Count, fill = Variable)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack") +  
  geom_text(aes(label = Count), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 3) + 
  facet_wrap(~ Variable, scales = "free_y", ncol = 1) +  
  labs(title = "Count of Variables Within the Top 10 Themes",
       x = "Theme",
       y = NULL,  
       fill = "Variable") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),  
        strip.text = element_text(size = 14), 
        panel.spacing = unit(1, "lines"),  
        panel.grid = element_blank(),  
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),  
        axis.text.y = element_blank(),  
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank())

3.19. Top 10 themes: total sets and average pieces per set.

Since last graph has interesting cases regarding variables such as pieces, we can compare the total amount of sets of the top 10 themes with the average pieces per set per theme. This will allow us to visualize which themes have higher amounts of pieces per set.

Surprisingly, Technic appears in both extremes in the two graphs. It is the last theme by the amount of total sets but the first in terms of average pieces per set per theme. Star Wars on the other hand shares second place in both graphs. Interestingly, Duplo offers the least average pieces per set while not being the last in terms of total sets.

top_themes <- lego_data %>%
  count(Theme, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10, n) %>%
  pull(Theme)


top_theme_data <- lego_data %>%
  filter(Theme %in% top_themes)


sets_per_theme <- top_theme_data %>%
  group_by(Theme) %>%
  summarize(total_sets = n(), .groups = 'drop')


avg_pieces_per_theme <- top_theme_data %>%
  group_by(Theme) %>%
  summarize(avg_pieces = mean(Pieces, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')


plot_total_sets <- ggplot(sets_per_theme, aes(x = reorder(Theme, -total_sets), y = total_sets, fill = Theme)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "turbo") +
  labs(title = "Total Number of Lego Sets by Theme", x = "Theme", y = "Total Sets") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "none",
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )


plot_avg_pieces <- ggplot(avg_pieces_per_theme, aes(x = reorder(Theme, -avg_pieces), y = avg_pieces, fill = Theme)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "turbo") +
  labs(title = "Average Number of Pieces per Set by Theme", x = "Theme", y = "Average Pieces per Set") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    legend.position = "none",
    panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )


grid.arrange(plot_total_sets, plot_avg_pieces, ncol = 2)

4. Conclusions

  1. 2020 experienced an important increase in total Lego sets.

  2. Most of the Lego sets come in small size, are sold in retail and use box as the main type of packaging.

  3. Behavioral changes in variables such as pieces, unique pieces and weight were not appreciated, resulting in constant distributions within the time period studied.

  4. All variables present positive correlations between them. Pieces and unique pieces seem to depend from each other.

  5. The vast majority of age groups (including the top 10) fall into the LegoKids category, which happen to also be the majority of Lego sets within the top 10 themes.

  6. Customer maturity (age groups) seems to be an important factor to determine the number of pieces.

  7. Star wars and City Lego sets presented the highest overall count on pieces, unique pieces and minifigures. Themes definitely can be predictor when it comes to these variables.

  8. While being last in the top 10 themes by the amount of Lego sets, Technic presents the highest average pieces per set, far from the second spot hold by Star Wars.

  9. Average unique pieces per set remained fairly similar within most of the top 10 themes. However, distribution of unique pieces was particularly narrow in BrickHeadz and Duplo.

  10. BrickHeadz and Technic were absent from the distribution of minifigures by the top 10 themes. City on the other hand had plenty of outliers.
